1
00:00:14,608 --> 00:00:16,530
Name: Rayan Riyad Khalil

2
00:00:17,570 --> 00:00:19,250
Born in 1987

3
00:00:20,476 --> 00:00:22,937
My clan is al-Sabaawi

4
00:00:24,050 --> 00:00:26,111
By God, our—my situation

5
00:00:27,435 --> 00:00:29,115
I was a driver on the Turkey route

6
00:00:30,319 --> 00:00:32,187
We took people and brought others

7
00:00:32,874 --> 00:00:34,590
And in the meantime

8
00:00:35,630 --> 00:00:36,716
I started having problems

9
00:00:36,763 --> 00:00:38,608
They started monitoring us, and so on

10
00:00:38,755 --> 00:00:40,036
And because of that our situation got worse

11
00:00:40,320 --> 00:00:43,467
The route was closed, and we had a shop in Ras al-Kour

12
00:00:44,144 --> 00:00:47,642
It was a barbershop belonging to my brothers

13
00:00:48,258 --> 00:00:51,035
Being there meant I didn’t have a job

14
00:00:51,523 --> 00:00:56,436
We started transporting people and taking them to…

15
00:00:57,182 --> 00:01:01,375
We took them from here to Raqqa, and from Raqqa they went to Turkey

16
00:01:02,281 --> 00:01:03,360
And during this time

17
00:01:03,872 --> 00:01:07,013
Once or twice I was caught, and so on

18
00:01:07,755 --> 00:01:09,660
So I was being watched closely

19
00:01:11,514 --> 00:01:14,477
They kept following me a lot, I was under surveillance

20
00:01:15,249 --> 00:01:16,643
I felt I was being watched

21
00:01:21,098 --> 00:01:24,918
The detention happened at our shop

22
00:01:25,139 --> 00:01:27,415
In Ras al-Kour we had a shop, a barbershop

23
00:01:28,392 --> 00:01:29,831
The detention happened there

24
00:01:31,218 --> 00:01:33,723
A car with three men arrived, a car from the <i>Hisba</i>

25
00:01:35,603 --> 00:01:37,470
They got out, and I was standing in the street

26
00:01:38,727 --> 00:01:42,363
They arrested me on the spot, took my phones, searched me, and brought me to this place

27
00:01:43,598 --> 00:01:46,065
Interviewer: Was there an informant against you?

28
00:01:46,235 --> 00:01:48,926
Yes, there was a clue, but no proof

29
00:01:50,232 --> 00:01:52,080
In the end

30
00:01:54,080 --> 00:01:56,051
He said, We just want any proof against you

31
00:01:56,137 --> 00:01:57,753
And as for the rest, we know how to deal with you

32
00:01:57,817 --> 00:02:00,783
Interviewer: When they came to arrest you, did they come asking for you by name?

33
00:02:00,882 --> 00:02:01,883
Or was there more than one person?

34
00:02:02,056 --> 00:02:03,372
No, me personally

35
00:02:03,835 --> 00:02:05,714
Interviewer: So there was an informant against you?

36
00:02:05,828 --> 00:02:09,222
Yes, there was some tip, but I don’t know what it was

37
00:02:09,535 --> 00:02:12,932
Interviewer: Was it someone you knew, or one of your friends?

38
00:02:13,159 --> 00:02:17,164
Or someone you dealt with in your life through work?

39
00:02:17,318 --> 00:02:20,163
Honestly, there was a young man, and he’s gone now

40
00:02:20,370 --> 00:02:22,510
We had some problems between us, and he was killed in the shelling

41
00:02:23,224 --> 00:02:28,021
After some time, after the liberation, they said that so-and-so, son of so-and-so, was the one

42
00:02:28,128 --> 00:02:31,054
Who informed, and he had a car, and that kind of thing

43
00:02:31,731 --> 00:02:33,957
And he worked transporting people

44
00:02:35,278 --> 00:02:40,469
Interviewer: When did they bring you to this prison? Was it at <i>maghreb</i> [sunset], <i>isha</i> [evening], or at noon?

45
00:02:40,569 --> 00:02:41,792
No, no, at <i>maghreb</i>

46
00:02:42,520 --> 00:02:45,438
Between <i>asr</i> [afternoon] and <i>maghreb</i>, and it was raining

47
00:02:45,790 --> 00:02:50,304
Interviewer: The three people you mentioned. Were they from Mosul or from outside Mosul?

48
00:02:50,364 --> 00:02:52,534
No, their driver was from Mosul

49
00:02:53,131 --> 00:02:55,124
A young man named Mahmoud, and we

50
00:02:55,331 --> 00:02:58,326
And the other two, one was thin and dark-skinned, tall

51
00:02:58,640 --> 00:03:01,525
He was from the countryside or something like that

52
00:03:01,892 --> 00:03:04,200
He wasn’t from Mosul, but the driver was from Mosul

53
00:03:05,360 --> 00:03:06,518
From his accent and the way he spoke

54
00:03:11,362 --> 00:03:14,473
When they first brought us in through the door, there was a prefab room

55
00:03:14,860 --> 00:03:16,269
He leaves you standing in the prefab room

56
00:03:16,910 --> 00:03:21,255
He takes whatever personal items you have, he takes your belongings

57
00:03:21,752 --> 00:03:24,333
After you are handed to him by a <i>Hisba</i> member

58
00:03:25,207 --> 00:03:28,050
The <i>Hisba</i> member who brought you in the car hands you over to the man in the room

59
00:03:28,497 --> 00:03:31,697
Then other men come, take you, and escort you to the holding area

60
00:03:32,197 --> 00:03:35,323
Inside the prefab room he blindfolded me

61
00:03:36,496 --> 00:03:38,318
And he took me some distance

62
00:03:38,893 --> 00:03:41,370
But I knew I was still inside the church

63
00:03:41,729 --> 00:03:43,568
But where inside it he took me, I don’t know

64
00:03:44,135 --> 00:03:47,594
About 15 to 20 meters on foot

65
00:03:47,901 --> 00:03:49,544
And we went up the stairs and entered the room

66
00:03:49,851 --> 00:03:50,891
And when we entered

67
00:03:51,319 --> 00:03:54,856
The total number there was about seven, eight, or nine, around that

68
00:03:56,090 --> 00:03:59,425
When you go in, you’re terrified, you don’t know what your fate will be

69
00:03:59,759 --> 00:04:03,067
You might be released or kept, die, be executed, or be killed, you don’t know

70
00:04:03,847 --> 00:04:06,999
I saw elderly prisoners

71
00:04:07,320 --> 00:04:08,629
And there were young ones too

72
00:04:08,843 --> 00:04:10,237
And some were brought in for smoking

73
00:04:10,585 --> 00:04:12,277
Or because of their pants

74
00:04:12,850 --> 00:04:14,367
Or for not keeping up with prayer

75
00:04:15,328 --> 00:04:17,747
Or for walking in the street, and so on

76
00:04:17,880 --> 00:04:19,147
For many other things

77
00:04:19,610 --> 00:04:22,656
They kept bringing two or three in and taking others out, nonstop like that

78
00:04:23,250 --> 00:04:26,204
There were two who stayed, I was taken out, and they remained there

79
00:04:26,718 --> 00:04:27,806
Interviewer: What were their charges?

80
00:04:27,893 --> 00:04:33,192
Their charges—I don’t know, they had problems and there was a case against them

81
00:04:34,174 --> 00:04:35,494
Related to women or something like that

82
00:04:35,607 --> 00:04:38,535
As I remember, because their case was very serious

83
00:04:38,920 --> 00:04:40,977
According to what I heard from someone

84
00:04:42,084 --> 00:04:44,518
Interviewer: Do you mean their case was about women?
Witness: Yes, because of women

85
00:04:44,629 --> 00:04:47,510
Interviewer: So the case was among themselves? No one had filed a complaint against them?

86
00:04:47,630 --> 00:04:51,216
No, no, I mean they were caught in the act with women

87
00:04:51,346 --> 00:04:52,360
Interviewer: Do you mean an adultery case?

88
00:04:52,475 --> 00:04:55,568
Yes, an adultery case, and those two were with one woman

89
00:04:55,657 --> 00:04:57,610
And for that reason they were kept here

90
00:04:57,943 --> 00:05:02,438
Interviewer: The woman who was with them, did they tell you which court they took her to?

91
00:05:02,533 --> 00:05:05,083
No, no, they took the woman

92
00:05:05,430 --> 00:05:06,646
But they put her in a different place

93
00:05:06,980 --> 00:05:09,132
Interviewer: Was there a women’s prison in this place?

94
00:05:09,599 --> 00:05:11,007
You can expect anything from them

95
00:05:11,174 --> 00:05:14,542
Because there are many rooms, this one and others

96
00:05:14,703 --> 00:05:16,618
And on the other side, that was also a prison

97
00:05:17,958 --> 00:05:19,858
Interviewer: So you didn’t hear women’s voices?

98
00:05:20,198 --> 00:05:24,385
No, I didn’t, but there were sounds of torture

99
00:05:24,502 --> 00:05:26,618
Mostly at night and at dawn, especially at night

100
00:05:28,023 --> 00:05:31,288
Interviewer: How many days did you stay in this room, which is a cell?

101
00:05:31,462 --> 00:05:33,196
About eight days or nine days

102
00:05:33,490 --> 00:05:34,985
Interviewer: Eight days or nine days

103
00:05:36,176 --> 00:05:39,891
When you entered the room, did they take you straight to the judge for interrogation?

104
00:05:40,083 --> 00:05:42,350
Or did you stay for a while, and then they took you to the Investigative Judge?

105
00:05:42,615 --> 00:05:45,107
No, I stayed until the second day, then they referred me to the judge

106
00:05:49,599 --> 00:05:54,091
Of course, when they took you to the judge, your eyes were blindfolded and they would lift the blindfold in front of the judge

107
00:05:56,493 --> 00:05:58,843
He said, You're before the judge

108
00:06:00,237 --> 00:06:05,828
He started by asking me about prayer and about religion, and there was a group sitting beside him

109
00:06:07,669 --> 00:06:11,968
Interviewer: What kind of questions did he ask you?

110
00:06:12,082 --> 00:06:14,675
About prayer, Do you pray? I answered, Yes

111
00:06:15,479 --> 00:06:17,816
I told him, Yes. He said, Do you know how to recite the call to prayer? I told him, Yes

112
00:06:17,996 --> 00:06:21,173
He said—Get up and recite the call to prayer. I tried the call to prayer, but I didn't do it well

113
00:06:22,006 --> 00:06:24,325
He said—This one didn't use to pray, he was lying to us

114
00:06:26,298 --> 00:06:32,821
He said—He must learn the call to prayer and the prayer, and so on

115
00:06:33,278 --> 00:06:37,192
He would ask you with a hard stare when he spoke to you

116
00:06:37,719 --> 00:06:41,605
In a way that makes you afraid even of yourself

117
00:06:46,165 --> 00:06:48,045
No, he is the one who asks you about this

118
00:06:49,927 --> 00:06:52,956
Interviewer: During your interrogation, especially the first interrogation

119
00:06:53,373 --> 00:06:57,342
Did you feel he knew information about your life?

120
00:06:57,609 --> 00:07:00,201
Did he mention any details that no one knew except you and your family?

121
00:07:00,354 --> 00:07:04,398
No, he knew this, but he didn't say it directly

122
00:07:04,469 --> 00:07:05,529
Interviewer: How did you know that?

123
00:07:05,717 --> 00:07:11,139
I mean, it was obvious, he would ask you questions like, You meet with so-and-so, or you go to such-and-such a place

124
00:07:12,278 --> 00:07:15,606
He had information, but who supplied him with it, I don't know

125
00:07:16,043 --> 00:07:20,384
But he told me at that time—This is your last warning

126
00:07:20,504 --> 00:07:23,504
But next time, the punishment will be different

127
00:07:23,875 --> 00:07:28,340
He threatened me, and after I got out I was under surveillance

128
00:07:29,280 --> 00:07:32,974
Whenever I went anywhere, there were one or two people watching me

129
00:07:33,121 --> 00:07:35,385
And in the end, I was being watched

130
00:07:35,494 --> 00:07:41,185
But in the end, I left Iraq

131
00:07:42,320 --> 00:07:43,980
Interviewer: About the judge who was interrogating you

132
00:07:44,373 --> 00:07:45,753
And since you were the one who shaved his hair

133
00:07:45,880 --> 00:07:47,326
Can you describe his features for us?

134
00:07:47,586 --> 00:07:49,950
And about how old he was, his appearance, and the clothes he wore?

135
00:07:50,049 --> 00:07:52,644
As for clothes, he wore black and a black turban

136
00:07:53,219 --> 00:07:57,811
And his beard was like this, and his age was between forty and forty-one, or about forty-two years

137
00:07:58,071 --> 00:07:59,641
Interviewer: Was his dialect Standard Arabic or the dialect of Mosul?

138
00:07:59,855 --> 00:08:01,892
No, no, the dialect was different, he wasn't from Mosul

139
00:08:02,745 --> 00:08:04,551
Interviewer: Standard Arabic or rural? Witness: No, rural

140
00:08:06,071 --> 00:08:07,165
Interviewer: Meaning from the outskirts?

141
00:08:07,577 --> 00:08:08,289
Yes, from the outskirts

142
00:08:08,570 --> 00:08:10,365
From the outskirts of the city

143
00:08:11,252 --> 00:08:14,081
Interviewer: The other people, about how old were they?

144
00:08:14,253 --> 00:08:16,650
Some were in their thirties and also in their twenties

145
00:08:17,250 --> 00:08:19,231
They were from their group, and they were sitting

146
00:08:19,690 --> 00:08:23,882
Interviewer: From their appearance, were they leaders or ordinary people?

147
00:08:23,982 --> 00:08:28,502
No, no, they were leaders, carrying pistols and walkie-talkies

148
00:08:29,368 --> 00:08:31,816
Interviewer: During the judge's interrogation with you?

149
00:08:32,083 --> 00:08:33,922
Regarding what was said to you directly

150
00:08:34,250 --> 00:08:38,389
Interviewer: Did any of the people there ask you a question, or was it only the judge who asked?

151
00:08:38,489 --> 00:08:42,025
No, only the judge, but later the one who sat next to the judge

152
00:08:42,765 --> 00:08:46,984
When prayer was mentioned, he told the judge that this man does not pray

153
00:08:47,607 --> 00:08:51,381
He said, It is obvious—if he prayed, made the call to prayer, and was observant

154
00:08:51,508 --> 00:08:55,745
He would not be answering this way, hesitating and making mistakes

155
00:08:56,680 --> 00:09:00,360
Interviewer: During the judge’s interrogation, was there someone next to him writing it down?

156
00:09:00,471 --> 00:09:03,117
Yes, he was writing, he was writing on a sheet of paper

157
00:09:03,824 --> 00:09:06,735
On a sheet of paper, he was writing

158
00:09:07,063 --> 00:09:11,812
For example—Why did you answer incorrectly to such and such a question?

159
00:09:12,286 --> 00:09:16,269
And your details—where you go, when you come, whom you meet, and whom you walk with

160
00:09:16,756 --> 00:09:19,419
And which grade I was in, he had a lot of information about me

161
00:09:19,879 --> 00:09:23,035
He asked me about them, and I had forgotten them, I had forgotten

162
00:09:23,736 --> 00:09:24,740
Interviewer: Like what?

163
00:09:24,842 --> 00:09:27,630
For example, he told me, You used to work

164
00:09:28,296 --> 00:09:32,711
On the road to Turkey, transporting people and bringing people, and things like that

165
00:09:33,204 --> 00:09:38,471
He asked me questions—I can tell you he was someone who knew a lot about me

166
00:09:39,120 --> 00:09:42,372
When I went in and he started talking to me, I was surprised by what he said

167
00:09:43,199 --> 00:09:45,267
Like someone who knows you personally

168
00:09:46,333 --> 00:09:51,773
Interviewer: Did he ask questions about your presence in your neighborhood?

169
00:09:52,151 --> 00:09:56,045
He asked me about my home, and about my children, how many children I have

170
00:09:56,144 --> 00:09:58,329
Married or single, and so on

171
00:09:58,592 --> 00:10:01,232
And what I have, where I go, and whom I walk with

172
00:10:02,233 --> 00:10:05,038
Even that I used to sit at my friend’s place and he had an electric generator

173
00:10:05,652 --> 00:10:09,121
He said—So you were mostly at the generator at night

174
00:10:10,801 --> 00:10:14,259
Interviewer: Did he ask about specific people to get information about them, and who were they?

175
00:10:14,627 --> 00:10:17,547
Who? No, he did not ask me that

176
00:10:18,068 --> 00:10:20,880
But I felt inside

177
00:10:21,580 --> 00:10:23,470
That I was under surveillance, and he said this

178
00:10:25,177 --> 00:10:28,231
He said, This time we pardoned you, but the second time

179
00:10:28,805 --> 00:10:31,169
We will execute you immediately when we find anything against you

180
00:10:35,747 --> 00:10:38,719
In the first session, I was sentenced because of prayer

181
00:10:39,393 --> 00:10:43,110
And there was an education center, and they made me go there to learn, and so on

182
00:10:44,073 --> 00:10:46,820
Interviewer: You mean to attend a school and classes?

183
00:10:46,834 --> 00:10:50,024
School and classes, meaning they want to brainwash you

184
00:10:50,147 --> 00:10:52,762
Meaning they say this and that, they want to bring you onto their path

185
00:10:53,823 --> 00:10:58,561
They teach you and tell you that they came here for such and such

186
00:10:58,975 --> 00:11:03,922
And that some of them became martyrs, and that you must do such and such, and that your country is a Muslim country, and things like that

187
00:11:04,463 --> 00:11:07,925
Interviewer: Were the school and the classes in this same building?

188
00:11:08,005 --> 00:11:09,005
Yes, in this building

189
00:11:09,330 --> 00:11:13,715
Interviewer: Were there certain days and specific times and hours for the classes?

190
00:11:14,042 --> 00:11:17,332
The classes were every Sunday and Wednesday

191
00:11:17,722 --> 00:11:21,018
About an hour and a half or two hours, an hour and a half for lessons

192
00:11:21,508 --> 00:11:22,508
So twice a week?

193
00:11:22,609 --> 00:11:23,615
Yes, twice a week

194
00:11:24,501 --> 00:11:27,540
There were people who finished—there was nothing against them

195
00:11:27,914 --> 00:11:31,946
But because of prayer, he was obliged to come back—he would be released but had to keep attending

196
00:11:32,406 --> 00:11:36,031
The first teacher, as usual, was one of them

197
00:11:36,125 --> 00:11:39,146
He wore the same clothes they wore

198
00:11:40,006 --> 00:11:43,412
Yes, he was from Mosul

199
00:11:44,811 --> 00:11:48,622
He was from Mosul—he was the one teaching us

200
00:11:49,583 --> 00:11:51,821
Interviewer: Tell us about how the teaching was done. How was it carried out?

201
00:11:52,538 --> 00:11:56,508
There are seats, people sit, and he teaches you

202
00:11:56,583 --> 00:11:58,579
About religious matters, and we’re like this

203
00:11:58,692 --> 00:12:02,433
We came to fight for you, and you should be with us, your brothers are fighting

204
00:12:02,767 --> 00:12:05,043
He teaches you these things, he wants to convince you

205
00:12:05,550 --> 00:12:07,806
Interviewer: Did he focus on certain topics?

206
00:12:08,195 --> 00:12:13,462
Yes, they had certain things, he says you must apply them and be with the brothers

207
00:12:13,602 --> 00:12:16,804
You must defend your honor and other matters to pull you into many things

208
00:12:16,924 --> 00:12:21,990
Interviewer: Like what? Did they call on you to be among the fighters and the mujahideen as they call them?

209
00:12:22,215 --> 00:12:26,977
While talking to you, if it were up to him, he would say—Come and sign to join us

210
00:12:27,698 --> 00:12:30,710
But he wants to bring you to this path gradually

211
00:12:31,364 --> 00:12:33,495
Interviewer: Did he invite you or someone else directly?

212
00:12:33,502 --> 00:12:36,710
He would say—Go out and come, commit

213
00:12:37,171 --> 00:12:39,845
Be with your brothers, go and fight, and so on

214
00:12:40,492 --> 00:12:41,748
He tells you this

215
00:12:42,415 --> 00:12:44,628
Interviewer: So this was the style of the lesson he taught?

216
00:12:44,908 --> 00:12:50,676
As you said, they sentenced you to be taught prayer, fasting, purification, and the call to prayer

217
00:12:50,998 --> 00:12:56,107
And now you’re telling us about other topics related to what they call jihad or to details of fighting

218
00:12:56,247 --> 00:12:59,504
He was the one who taught us, and the first thing he teaches

219
00:13:00,348 --> 00:13:06,407
First he teaches you prayer, how many units of prayer, and about the call to prayer, and so on

220
00:13:07,018 --> 00:13:08,533
That was the lesson

221
00:13:08,746 --> 00:13:12,392
Then in the second lesson, at the same time, he teaches you these matters

222
00:13:13,520 --> 00:13:15,005
Interviewer: What exactly did he teach you?

223
00:13:15,093 --> 00:13:22,064
He tells you, Go out and fight like the brothers, be with them, and don’t give the enemy a chance to win

224
00:13:22,644 --> 00:13:25,981
And so on, he teaches you these matters

225
00:13:26,329 --> 00:13:31,162
Interviewer: So you didn’t know exactly who the enemy he wanted you to fight was?

226
00:13:31,415 --> 00:13:38,893
I want to ask, did you consider yourselves enemies to them inside the prison?

227
00:13:38,967 --> 00:13:39,985
Yes, that’s right

228
00:13:40,076 --> 00:13:43,781
Interviewer: Were you considered an enemy on the same level as the one they fought?

229
00:13:43,857 --> 00:13:50,028
For him, since you are not with him, he considers you his enemy

230
00:13:54,979 --> 00:13:56,712
There were people they brought in

231
00:13:57,434 --> 00:13:59,979
They kept them blindfolded inside

232
00:14:00,900 --> 00:14:02,340
One day they brought a man

233
00:14:03,032 --> 00:14:06,384
They brought him maybe at night, he stayed blindfolded until the next day

234
00:14:07,618 --> 00:14:11,112
Sitting in a corner, what his story was or his fate, we didn’t know

235
00:14:11,879 --> 00:14:12,938
And you couldn’t ask him

236
00:14:13,558 --> 00:14:14,558
And he couldn’t ask you

237
00:14:15,615 --> 00:14:16,683
And you couldn’t approach him

238
00:14:17,343 --> 00:14:19,479
They sat him there, and the next day they took him

239
00:14:20,811 --> 00:14:25,775
Interviewer: This person they brought blindfolded and you didn’t talk to him

240
00:14:25,881 --> 00:14:29,612
Did you receive an order from the jailer or guard not to approach him?

241
00:14:29,699 --> 00:14:32,702
From the moment they brought him in, they told him—Stay like this

242
00:14:33,963 --> 00:14:35,265
Stay in this position

243
00:14:36,179 --> 00:14:38,125
I don’t want to hear anything from you

244
00:14:38,465 --> 00:14:40,377
Interviewer: Did he order you not to talk to him?

245
00:14:40,557 --> 00:14:46,000
Who? When he was talking to him like this, we, out of fear, didn’t talk to him

246
00:14:46,316 --> 00:14:49,331
And we couldn’t ask him, we didn’t know why they’d brought him here

247
00:14:49,762 --> 00:14:51,980
The next day they came and took him away

248
00:14:52,641 --> 00:14:55,666
There was the sound of screaming, but we didn’t see him after that

249
00:14:56,307 --> 00:15:00,638
Interviewer: While this person was isolated and forbidden to talk to

250
00:15:00,678 --> 00:15:05,137
It was as if he had some kind of special immunity or special guard

251
00:15:05,498 --> 00:15:08,778
After a full night, how did this person relieve himself?

252
00:15:09,599 --> 00:15:12,697
He did not relieve himself, he even left without relieving himself

253
00:15:13,531 --> 00:15:14,616
They did not even give him water

254
00:15:15,659 --> 00:15:16,859
How would he relieve himself?

255
00:15:17,685 --> 00:15:18,805
There was a spy

256
00:15:19,288 --> 00:15:22,327
We knew this, and there was a person who would come and sit

257
00:15:22,861 --> 00:15:26,439
He said these people were bad, and of course he was with them

258
00:15:27,412 --> 00:15:29,779
You were afraid to say a single word

259
00:15:30,301 --> 00:15:32,655
Then he would talk to you about other things, and he would press you with questions

260
00:15:34,078 --> 00:15:36,740
He kept pressing with questions a lot

261
00:15:37,474 --> 00:15:38,659
Interviewer: What did he ask about?

262
00:15:38,787 --> 00:15:43,126
He asked us how they had brought us, what this place was, and how they had humiliated us over a cigarette

263
00:15:43,240 --> 00:15:45,573
And whether it was worth it, and so on

264
00:15:45,633 --> 00:15:49,886
He wanted you to say those people were not good, but he was working with them

265
00:15:51,033 --> 00:15:54,867
He wanted to get new information from you, to entrap you

266
00:15:59,641 --> 00:16:04,148
Sometimes it came in a pot, and sometimes in a bowl, depending on the meal

267
00:16:04,254 --> 00:16:09,720
There was no special food, the food was served to everyone, they did not have specific food for anyone

268
00:16:10,324 --> 00:16:11,344
Interviewer: What kind of food?

269
00:16:11,464 --> 00:16:16,299
Rice, and sometimes in the morning yogurt, and things like that

270
00:16:16,361 --> 00:16:17,493
Interviewer: What was for breakfast?

271
00:16:17,687 --> 00:16:19,208
Yogurt and the like, and bread

272
00:16:19,548 --> 00:16:21,788
Interviewer: What was given to each person or prisoner?

273
00:16:21,842 --> 00:16:23,965
There was no portion for each person, at noon they brought a big platter of rice and meat

274
00:16:24,828 --> 00:16:28,456
Or they brought a pot of food, and everyone ate together

275
00:16:28,884 --> 00:16:29,885
Everyone was the same

276
00:16:30,181 --> 00:16:32,460
Whether you were full, ate, or did not eat

277
00:16:32,674 --> 00:16:35,594
You could not tell him you were hungry, and you could not say, Bring me more food

278
00:16:36,324 --> 00:16:40,156
Interviewer: For example, in the morning did each person have a specific <i>samoon</i> [bread roll]?

279
00:16:40,234 --> 00:16:43,740
No, a bag of <i>samoon</i> would come and everyone sat to eat

280
00:16:44,278 --> 00:16:46,563
Interviewer: How much was your share of <i>samoon</i>, one piece or two?

281
00:16:46,843 --> 00:16:51,177
Some ate three pieces of <i>samoon</i>, some two, and some did not eat out of distress

282
00:16:51,846 --> 00:16:53,143
Interviewer: Was the <i>samoon</i> enough?

283
00:16:53,586 --> 00:16:54,889
Interviewer: Did any <i>samoon</i> remain?

284
00:16:54,976 --> 00:16:57,171
No, none of it was left

285
00:16:58,758 --> 00:17:02,416
Interviewer: In your view, was this food cooked inside this building or did it come from outside?

286
00:17:02,644 --> 00:17:04,336
No, it likely came from outside this building

287
00:17:05,260 --> 00:17:08,970
That is obvious, if it was cooked in this building there would have been a smell of food

288
00:17:09,411 --> 00:17:11,576
It could have been cooked here and we did not know

289
00:17:12,173 --> 00:17:14,966
Because you were in a room and did not know your fate

290
00:17:15,926 --> 00:17:21,792
Because of fear and anxiety, nothing stayed in your head

291
00:17:22,077 --> 00:17:24,639
Interviewer: Was there any change in the food? For example, today rice

292
00:17:24,750 --> 00:17:27,546
Tomorrow bulgur and then chickpeas? Or was it all rice?

293
00:17:27,716 --> 00:17:29,878
No, just rice and beans, and things like that

294
00:17:31,238 --> 00:17:33,652
Interviewer: Was it the same type of food the whole time? Witness: Yes

295
00:17:33,955 --> 00:17:38,185
There was, for example, a time when they had a feast

296
00:17:38,479 --> 00:17:40,032
They would give us whatever was left over from it

297
00:17:40,957 --> 00:17:43,169
They gave their leftovers to the prisoners

298
00:17:43,883 --> 00:17:47,177
Interviewer: Was the rice mixed with the broth, or separate?

299
00:17:47,364 --> 00:17:48,644
No, it was separate

300
00:17:49,315 --> 00:17:51,855
Interviewer: The containers they served in, were they plastic?

301
00:17:51,943 --> 00:17:53,509
Made of plastic, plastic

302
00:17:53,863 --> 00:17:56,677
Interviewer: Did you have tea?

303
00:17:56,958 --> 00:17:59,163
Tea was scarce, it was served only in the morning

304
00:18:00,486 --> 00:18:02,573
Interviewer: Did they serve you tea?
Witness: Only in the morning

305
00:18:03,549 --> 00:18:04,958
Interviewer: A cup for each person?

306
00:18:05,025 --> 00:18:09,591
No, no, it came in a thermos

307
00:18:10,765 --> 00:18:13,727
It was enough if each person drank one cup

308
00:18:14,544 --> 00:18:17,757
Interviewer: Were the cups plastic?
Witness: Yes, plastic

309
00:18:18,459 --> 00:18:19,925
Interviewer: When they brought in the food

310
00:18:20,365 --> 00:18:22,592
Did the jailer open the door and bring in the food?

311
00:18:22,754 --> 00:18:27,903
Or would he open the door and call one of you that the food was outside, come take it?

312
00:18:28,582 --> 00:18:33,451
As soon as he brought the food, he would hand it through the door and anyone would take it from him

313
00:18:33,977 --> 00:18:34,977
And he would leave and close the door

314
00:18:35,601 --> 00:18:39,202
Before he served the food, you had finished the previous meal and collected it in a bag

315
00:18:39,262 --> 00:18:40,762
He would take the bag and give you the second meal

316
00:18:41,359 --> 00:18:43,924
Interviewer: Did you have water available, drinking water?

317
00:18:44,017 --> 00:18:48,811
Water was available, drinking water, and if it was cut off there was water from the tank

318
00:18:49,257 --> 00:18:52,960
Interviewer: Did each person have a specific share, or could you ask at any time?

319
00:18:53,798 --> 00:18:55,418
No, there was no specific share

320
00:18:55,773 --> 00:18:58,363
They brought water for drinking, and there would be some left

321
00:19:02,781 --> 00:19:04,263
In the same room there was a toilet

322
00:19:04,350 --> 00:19:06,013
The toilet door was open twenty-four hours

323
00:19:07,116 --> 00:19:10,808
You could relieve yourself whenever you wanted

324
00:19:10,975 --> 00:19:13,738
But in the morning you had to wake up

325
00:19:14,172 --> 00:19:16,637
For prayer at the right time

326
00:19:16,951 --> 00:19:18,379
After the call to prayer, you prayed

327
00:19:18,693 --> 00:19:21,546
Anyone could be the imam and we would pray

328
00:19:22,169 --> 00:19:23,612
Interviewer: Was the imam one of the prisoners?

329
00:19:23,724 --> 00:19:24,932
Yes, one of the prisoners

330
00:19:25,494 --> 00:19:27,601
Interviewer: Did they come to pray with you? Witness: Who do you mean?

331
00:19:27,871 --> 00:19:29,306
Interviewer: The jailers? Witness: No

332
00:19:29,699 --> 00:19:32,547
The jailers prayed, even those who hadn’t been praying

333
00:19:32,756 --> 00:19:34,367
Interviewer: Not the prisoners? Rather the jailer?

334
00:19:34,453 --> 00:19:36,686
No, we didn’t see him

335
00:19:36,853 --> 00:19:41,743
Only if there was an interrogation with you, or they wanted information from you, he would come to take you

336
00:19:41,856 --> 00:19:44,262
Otherwise you stayed in the prison

337
00:19:44,551 --> 00:19:48,461
But at the dawn prayer he would come to wake you; even if you were asleep he would knock on the door

338
00:19:48,940 --> 00:19:51,023
For prayer… prayer… he calls you to prayer

339
00:19:51,575 --> 00:19:57,409
Interviewer: Regarding the toilet, were you able to take your time when you relieved yourself?

340
00:19:57,516 --> 00:20:00,331
No, we were not comfortable—since we entered we did not feel comfortable

341
00:20:00,425 --> 00:20:02,081
Because you do not know your fate

342
00:20:02,195 --> 00:20:04,961
Someone would tell you they would execute you

343
00:20:05,071 --> 00:20:08,017
Another would say they would kill you, and another would say they would cut off your hand

344
00:20:08,217 --> 00:20:11,454
You do not know what your fate is

345
00:20:12,194 --> 00:20:19,227
Interviewer: The water in the toilet—was it hot, warm, or cold?

346
00:20:19,533 --> 00:20:21,547
No, it was tank water, from the tank

347
00:20:21,974 --> 00:20:24,355
Interviewer: Was it always available, or did it get cut off?

348
00:20:24,750 --> 00:20:27,287
It was from the tank, whenever you opened the tap it was there

349
00:20:27,417 --> 00:20:30,571
Cleaning was required, and what did we even have that needed cleaning in the first place

350
00:20:31,067 --> 00:20:32,148
You didn’t have cigarettes

351
00:20:32,815 --> 00:20:33,885
Only leftover food

352
00:20:34,392 --> 00:20:37,678
And the extra water and food, that was the cleaning they had

353
00:20:38,058 --> 00:20:39,112
You had nothing with you

354
00:20:39,353 --> 00:20:40,959
Interviewer: Was there a garbage container?

355
00:20:41,032 --> 00:20:42,773
There were bags you could tie shut

356
00:20:43,316 --> 00:20:49,451
When they gave you food, you tied the bag and threw it at the door, and he would take it

357
00:20:49,746 --> 00:20:51,828
Interviewer: While you were in this place, did you have cleaning supplies?

358
00:20:51,958 --> 00:20:56,112
Like soap, dishwashing liquid, or disinfectants?

359
00:20:56,279 --> 00:21:01,135
No disinfectants, just soap when leaving the toilet

360
00:21:01,276 --> 00:21:04,622
Interviewer: Was the soap enough for you? Witness: It was enough

361
00:21:05,836 --> 00:21:08,679
There were two bars, one for washing hands

362
00:21:09,093 --> 00:21:12,032
And for whoever wanted, like one time

363
00:21:12,239 --> 00:21:16,965
One prisoner told them, I’m <i>janoub</i> [ritually impure], so they told him, Go shower

364
00:21:17,249 --> 00:21:20,126
It was the same place used as both the shower and the toilet

365
00:21:20,890 --> 00:21:21,989
And there were two towels as well

366
00:21:23,076 --> 00:21:28,650
Interviewer: For showering, was it whenever you wanted?

367
00:21:28,778 --> 00:21:34,787
Not whenever you wanted, maybe every two or three days someone would shower

368
00:21:35,256 --> 00:21:37,403
Interviewer: There was no shower schedule? Witness: No, no

369
00:21:38,496 --> 00:21:41,826
Interviewer: You were inside the cell and the toilet was with you too?

370
00:21:41,897 --> 00:21:43,279
The toilet was the same place for showering

371
00:21:43,976 --> 00:21:47,094
Interviewer: No one had authority over you in this matter, you could do it freely?

372
00:21:47,194 --> 00:21:48,201
Yes, we could do it freely

373
00:21:52,798 --> 00:21:55,192
Interviewer: Were you tortured? Did you experience torture?

374
00:21:55,298 --> 00:21:56,298
Only flogging

375
00:21:56,828 --> 00:21:59,656
Interviewer: Before the flogging, any other torture?

376
00:21:59,930 --> 00:22:04,382
No, they didn’t torture me, just flogging at that time

377
00:22:04,757 --> 00:22:06,633
Interviewer: Were there torture rooms?

378
00:22:06,805 --> 00:22:09,175
Yes, they had torture rooms in this place

379
00:22:09,735 --> 00:22:13,214
Interviewer: Were there prisoners with you who were taken for torture and brought back?

380
00:22:13,315 --> 00:22:14,525
Yes, many prisoners

381
00:22:14,805 --> 00:22:18,522
They took them for torture, and they beat them unbelievably

382
00:22:18,940 --> 00:22:21,140
Interviewer: They were with you in the same room? Witness: In the same room

383
00:22:21,227 --> 00:22:24,000
Some were moved to other rooms, and some were taken again

384
00:22:24,133 --> 00:22:27,921
Interviewer: The people you were close to, when they were taken for torture

385
00:22:28,159 --> 00:22:31,871
And brought back again, didn’t they tell you about the torture methods?

386
00:22:31,984 --> 00:22:36,767
The ones used on them, like the <i>falaqa</i> [foot whipping], flogging, electricity, or the <i>mazaref</i> [body piercing]?

387
00:22:36,861 --> 00:22:39,029
Everything, there were people they used everything on

388
00:22:39,495 --> 00:22:43,357
They would walk in on their feet, and return carried in a blanket

389
00:22:45,454 --> 00:22:46,775
Interviewer: Did they have torture marks?

390
00:22:46,840 --> 00:22:50,958
Yes, they showed torture marks, but as I told you before

391
00:22:51,432 --> 00:22:54,602
You couldn’t ask, What’s your story, what happened to you, and so on

392
00:22:54,762 --> 00:22:56,666
Interviewer: I mean, did they bring them back after torture?

393
00:22:56,950 --> 00:23:00,600
Was it obvious they had been tortured by skinning? Or flogging?

394
00:23:00,693 --> 00:23:03,401
Or with electricity, or hanging, and so on?

395
00:23:03,481 --> 00:23:05,966
No, there was electricity, and they hit them with a stick

396
00:23:06,310 --> 00:23:09,406
I mean their body was crushed, they hit them with a metal pipe

397
00:23:09,920 --> 00:23:12,631
Interviewer: Do you have a story about one of the people who was with you

398
00:23:12,751 --> 00:23:14,177
About the torture method used on him?

399
00:23:14,275 --> 00:23:16,522
They would take him for two or three days

400
00:23:16,575 --> 00:23:18,842
But it never happened to me

401
00:23:19,741 --> 00:23:21,681
Interviewer: It didn’t happen in front of you?
Witness: No, by God

402
00:23:22,143 --> 00:23:25,301
That’s according to what I had heard, that’s how it was

403
00:23:26,421 --> 00:23:29,475
Interviewer: At night, when you were in the room

404
00:23:29,568 --> 00:23:31,888
Did you hear screams of people being tortured?

405
00:23:32,560 --> 00:23:36,499
Yes, that happens, killing and screams

406
00:23:36,927 --> 00:23:38,332
But where did it come from? You don’t know

407
00:23:38,573 --> 00:23:39,962
Interviewer: Were the screams close or far?

408
00:23:40,070 --> 00:23:43,382
No, it wasn’t very far, I mean

409
00:23:46,039 --> 00:23:48,502
Interviewer: So do you think it was from the rooms next to you?

410
00:23:48,900 --> 00:23:52,840
I think so, and I’m sure they had a place for killing and torture

411
00:23:52,912 --> 00:23:56,156
Interviewer: Was the screaming clear?
Witness: Yes, clear, and loud screams

412
00:23:56,697 --> 00:23:58,293
Interviewer: All night or at a specific time?

413
00:23:58,645 --> 00:24:02,375
At night and in the early morning, this happens

414
00:24:03,193 --> 00:24:05,307
I heard about many who died under their torture

415
00:24:06,027 --> 00:24:08,660
Many people died during torture

416
00:24:11,465 --> 00:24:16,405
Interviewer: Are you saying, or did you hear, that they died from torture?

417
00:24:16,541 --> 00:24:18,227
What kinds of torture did they use?

418
00:24:18,541 --> 00:24:20,044
They tortured them in many ways

419
00:24:20,367 --> 00:24:22,979
Many, anything you can think of in torture

420
00:24:25,443 --> 00:24:27,177
Interviewer: About how many people?

421
00:24:27,524 --> 00:24:29,034
They tortured many people

422
00:24:30,141 --> 00:24:33,207
Many died from torture, and many collapsed from torture

423
00:24:33,328 --> 00:24:35,051
And many suffered other things because of torture

424
00:24:36,210 --> 00:24:40,234
There are people to this day who suffer illnesses as a result of torture

425
00:24:41,503 --> 00:24:44,492
Some got diabetes, some got high blood pressure, or had a stroke

426
00:24:44,839 --> 00:24:46,167
And some even got cancer

427
00:24:51,960 --> 00:24:55,249
Interviewer: How did you sleep in the room?

428
00:24:55,489 --> 00:24:58,596
Did you feel comfortable while sleeping?

429
00:24:59,038 --> 00:25:01,999
Honestly, there was no comfort

430
00:25:02,321 --> 00:25:04,824
First, fear, and second, planes all night

431
00:25:05,045 --> 00:25:08,733
And every minute, every moment you say, I’m dead

432
00:25:08,860 --> 00:25:11,385
Why? Because there is a chance we will be bombed

433
00:25:11,949 --> 00:25:13,606
Because of their coming and going

434
00:25:13,713 --> 00:25:15,961
You say, We will be bombed, this place will be bombed

435
00:25:16,602 --> 00:25:18,936
Especially when hearing the sound of airplanes

436
00:25:19,390 --> 00:25:21,102
Terror takes hold in your heart

437
00:25:21,708 --> 00:25:25,438
You sit and recite the <i>shahada</i>, and you brace yourself that you will die

438
00:25:26,339 --> 00:25:29,643
Interviewer: How did you spend the time during the day?

439
00:25:29,836 --> 00:25:33,790
We spent it sitting and reading a verse, and so on

440
00:25:34,783 --> 00:25:37,276
Interviewer: Were there Qurans inside the room?

441
00:25:37,769 --> 00:25:40,949
Yes, there were pages and so on

442
00:25:41,169 --> 00:25:45,312
But I still can’t read or write, I just held it for appearance

443
00:25:45,566 --> 00:25:48,682
Interviewer: The one who could read, did they force him to read or not?

444
00:25:48,788 --> 00:25:51,862
There were some who could read, with the Quran in hand, and they raised their voice

445
00:25:51,935 --> 00:25:53,415
They told him to read so the others with him would listen

446
00:25:56,003 --> 00:25:58,529
Interviewer: When you were inside the detention room

447
00:25:58,869 --> 00:26:03,652
Was there a camera pointed at you so that everything you did was visible?

448
00:26:03,774 --> 00:26:05,878
Were you visible to them inside the room?

449
00:26:06,529 --> 00:26:08,794
I don’t know, maybe there was a camera

450
00:26:08,928 --> 00:26:11,851
Maybe, but I don’t remember whether it was there or not

451
00:26:12,279 --> 00:26:14,217
But I remember there was a camera

452
00:26:14,965 --> 00:26:17,292
I remember, in the corner

453
00:26:17,368 --> 00:26:19,015
Interviewer: Did you think your rooms were monitored?

454
00:26:19,082 --> 00:26:20,902
Monitored, I remember, I swear to God

455
00:26:21,055 --> 00:26:23,411
But I’m not a hundred percent sure right now

456
00:26:24,077 --> 00:26:26,886
Interviewer: While you were in that room?

457
00:26:26,986 --> 00:26:30,354
Was there a display screen there?

458
00:26:30,747 --> 00:26:34,905
Did ISIS show you its videos on that screen?

459
00:26:36,099 --> 00:26:38,746
Execution videos, execution and amputation videos?

460
00:26:39,083 --> 00:26:41,857
And battles, were they shown?

461
00:26:42,355 --> 00:26:45,194
In that room we didn’t have it

462
00:26:46,085 --> 00:26:47,836
But after we left

463
00:26:48,476 --> 00:26:50,726
A young man who had been inside before asked me

464
00:26:50,860 --> 00:26:52,765
He said, They used to put it on a memory card

465
00:26:52,939 --> 00:26:55,421
And show us those things

466
00:26:56,254 --> 00:26:59,882
To keep fear in the prisoner’s heart

467
00:27:00,174 --> 00:27:01,194
Interviewer: In your room it wasn’t there?

468
00:27:01,294 --> 00:27:02,489
No, in our room it wasn’t there

469
00:27:02,562 --> 00:27:06,598
But the same thing was in the halls

470
00:27:07,057 --> 00:27:08,263
It was in other places

471
00:27:13,327 --> 00:27:14,799
They were annoyed with us

472
00:27:15,119 --> 00:27:16,314
But that happens

473
00:27:16,761 --> 00:27:20,078
Because you’re not one of their members

474
00:27:20,298 --> 00:27:23,279
Considering you’re in that place with them

475
00:27:23,819 --> 00:27:28,023
He tells you—We’re fighting for you, doing this and that, and we have martyrs

476
00:27:28,250 --> 00:27:31,315
We’re fighting in battles and you’re sitting here, you’re supposed to be with your brothers

477
00:27:31,435 --> 00:27:35,511
And so on, and he keeps talking, trying to convince you

478
00:27:36,045 --> 00:27:38,199
He wants to get that idea into your head and thinking

479
00:27:38,493 --> 00:27:40,103
Interviewer: How many guards were in the room with you?

480
00:27:41,343 --> 00:27:42,455
For us, there were two

481
00:27:43,136 --> 00:27:46,097
The guys called one Abu... I don’t remember his name

482
00:27:47,063 --> 00:27:48,063
And the other, Abu Shalaan

483
00:27:48,458 --> 00:27:51,068
Interviewer: Did they take shifts or were they together?

484
00:27:51,382 --> 00:27:53,285
No, each one separately, and sometimes both came

485
00:27:53,392 --> 00:27:56,374
And sometimes one would come, knock on the door, and say—We’re not hearing you anymore

486
00:27:57,231 --> 00:27:59,577
You’re not reading the Quran anymore, and so on

487
00:28:00,404 --> 00:28:05,531
Interviewer: During your time there, over twenty-four hours a day

488
00:28:05,960 --> 00:28:07,753
Were they the same ones or did they change?

489
00:28:07,827 --> 00:28:09,260
No, they changed, they changed

490
00:28:09,368 --> 00:28:10,700
Interviewer: How often did they change?

491
00:28:10,781 --> 00:28:15,186
Every two days, they didn’t stay in the same place

492
00:28:17,000 --> 00:28:21,094
Interviewer: Did the guards here participate in battles?

493
00:28:21,186 --> 00:28:24,068
Did they go out, return, and take part in fighting and support?

494
00:28:24,930 --> 00:28:26,586
When would they go out and come back?

495
00:28:26,971 --> 00:28:29,615
Sometimes there were alerts

496
00:28:30,440 --> 00:28:33,994
At times we’d say there’s no one here except us

497
00:28:34,085 --> 00:28:35,591
Especially when the airstrikes came

498
00:28:36,171 --> 00:28:39,721
We’d say only the prisoners might be here, we couldn’t hear their voices

499
00:28:40,689 --> 00:28:42,495
Then after three or four hours

500
00:28:42,756 --> 00:28:45,344
They might come, and you’d hear them moving back and forth

501
00:28:46,650 --> 00:28:48,603
Interviewer; Did you see yourselves as targeted?

502
00:28:48,683 --> 00:28:51,072
We were targeted, targeted one hundred percent

503
00:28:51,573 --> 00:28:54,110
Targeted—if not by them, then by the planes overhead

504
00:28:54,904 --> 00:28:57,138
We didn’t know in which minute we’d be struck

505
00:28:57,526 --> 00:29:03,120
Interviewer: While you were there and the planes arrived, they would withdraw from the whole building

506
00:29:03,376 --> 00:29:05,642
Did you expect that?

507
00:29:05,783 --> 00:29:08,266
Honestly, at times I

508
00:29:08,346 --> 00:29:11,649
Interviewer: Did you have a sense of what was happening outside and so on?

509
00:29:11,775 --> 00:29:15,468
Sometimes we heard the heavy sound of planes

510
00:29:16,247 --> 00:29:18,260
Here we didn’t hear any sound, there was no one

511
00:29:19,898 --> 00:29:23,597
We would say they’d left us here and we would be bombed while they were gone

512
00:29:25,300 --> 00:29:28,564
In that situation you don’t know what you will do, you are terrified

513
00:29:29,383 --> 00:29:35,090
Even when sleeping, you wake up suddenly from the planes, something terrifying

514
00:29:35,922 --> 00:29:42,205
Interviewer: Do they disappear from the building before you hear the planes, or while the planes are overhead do they vanish?

515
00:29:42,518 --> 00:29:47,003
As soon as the planes started flying, you didn’t hear any movement from them

516
00:29:47,362 --> 00:29:51,202
Interviewer: Do you think they knew the planes were coming?

517
00:29:51,322 --> 00:29:52,322
Honestly, I don’t know

518
00:29:52,421 --> 00:29:57,035
In my view, they knew about it

519
00:29:57,175 --> 00:29:58,845
I remember it happened to us two or three times

520
00:29:58,905 --> 00:30:04,253
And I said it was likely this building would be bombed, and they left us alone in it and departed

521
00:30:04,746 --> 00:30:06,039
We were desperate about that situation

522
00:30:06,300 --> 00:30:10,087
Interviewer: If this building, as they thought, was targeted

523
00:30:10,455 --> 00:30:15,509
Why didn’t they try to move you to another place if this building was targeted?

524
00:30:16,415 --> 00:30:17,415
Why didn’t they try to move you?

525
00:30:17,490 --> 00:30:23,487
One time we were here, and during the lesson heavy plane activity started

526
00:30:24,920 --> 00:30:29,820
He said—Immediately end the lesson and return every prisoner to his place

527
00:30:31,841 --> 00:30:33,511
Within a minute they dispersed quickly

528
00:30:34,593 --> 00:30:35,840
Meaning they even ended the lesson

529
00:30:35,993 --> 00:30:38,833
Interviewer: So he ordered them to disperse? Witness: Yes, to disperse

530
00:30:43,612 --> 00:30:48,272
Interviewer: While you were in the detention room, did any of you develop a chronic illness

531
00:30:48,385 --> 00:30:54,025
Or did someone get scabies or a skin disease

532
00:30:54,206 --> 00:31:00,447
Such that he needed special medical care, or to be moved to another place?

533
00:31:00,601 --> 00:31:04,066
No, that did not happen, but one day

534
00:31:04,160 --> 00:31:07,978
As I heard, someone became very ill and they transferred him to the hospital

535
00:31:09,898 --> 00:31:12,612
Interviewer: Did they take him to the hospital, or did a doctor come to you?

536
00:31:12,686 --> 00:31:14,212
No, to the hospital, no doctor came to us

537
00:31:14,712 --> 00:31:15,718
Interviewer: No doctor came to you?

538
00:31:15,812 --> 00:31:19,391
The one whose condition was critical from the start would be transferred to the hospital, as I heard

539
00:31:20,105 --> 00:31:22,225
Interviewer: Was the one taken to the hospital under guard?

540
00:31:22,459 --> 00:31:25,895
We didn’t know if they took him to the hospital or to the clinic

541
00:31:26,169 --> 00:31:28,228
We only knew they moved him to another place

542
00:31:28,519 --> 00:31:34,402
Interviewer: If you or one of the prisoners had a headache or his blood pressure rose

543
00:31:34,522 --> 00:31:37,412
Or got the flu or similar illnesses

544
00:31:37,825 --> 00:31:43,435
Would a doctor or a nurse come to provide you with treatment and health care?

545
00:31:43,675 --> 00:31:46,887
No, no, that didn’t happen with us, and no one asked us

546
00:31:48,384 --> 00:31:50,670
Interviewer: Didn’t you ever ask a jailer for treatment?

547
00:31:51,070 --> 00:31:54,642
No, no, but one day someone was talking and he said

548
00:31:55,330 --> 00:31:56,448
And he had been in the prison before me

549
00:31:57,155 --> 00:32:03,489
He said—There was a person with us, his condition was critical, he got very sick, and he had a chronic illness

550
00:32:03,622 --> 00:32:06,208
He had epilepsy—a nerve disorder—I think, or something like that

551
00:32:06,268 --> 00:32:09,444
He fell ill suddenly, and they came, took him, and transferred him to the hospital

552
00:32:09,647 --> 00:32:11,513
Interviewer: Did they bring him back? Witness: Yes, they brought him back

553
00:32:12,084 --> 00:32:15,277
They brought him the next day—they took him to the hospital or somewhere else, I don’t know

554
00:32:16,585 --> 00:32:18,217
To the hospital or somewhere else, I don’t know

555
00:32:22,904 --> 00:32:27,057
Interviewer: In this prison, were there visits from families and relatives?

556
00:32:27,667 --> 00:32:28,667
No, no

557
00:32:28,828 --> 00:32:29,895
Interviewer: Didn’t anyone visit you?

558
00:32:30,372 --> 00:32:33,818
No one visited me, and even if someone came to ask about me here, they would tell him I’m not here

559
00:32:34,883 --> 00:32:35,883
Interviewer: Anyone else?

560
00:32:35,943 --> 00:32:39,399
As for me, my father came and asked about me, and they told him I wasn’t here

561
00:32:40,158 --> 00:32:42,824
Even though I was detained with them, they said, He’s not with us

562
00:32:44,283 --> 00:32:45,845
Interviewer: There were no visits? Witness: No

563
00:32:46,178 --> 00:32:50,528
They send him to the Faisaliya Center and tell him, Ask about him there, he went and asked

564
00:32:50,888 --> 00:32:53,027
Interviewer: Were there any special visits for other people?

565
00:32:53,241 --> 00:32:56,431
I don’t know—as for me, my family came and asked about me, and they told them–Not here

566
00:33:01,047 --> 00:33:04,140
Interviewer: Tell us how you got out, the method and the form of your release

567
00:33:04,837 --> 00:33:06,696
I signed a pledge

568
00:33:06,763 --> 00:33:08,700
Interviewer: What did the pledge stipulate, what did you commit to?

569
00:33:08,854 --> 00:33:10,637
A pledge that if I was caught committing violations

570
00:33:10,851 --> 00:33:13,584
Like skipping prayer and the like, then my punishment would be tripled

571
00:33:14,405 --> 00:33:17,424
For now that’s what they decided for me—later we don’t know what they’ll decide

572
00:33:17,839 --> 00:33:20,739
Your situation becomes frightening later if they catch you a second time

573
00:33:21,700 --> 00:33:25,786
And anyone who goes in to them becomes monitored afterward, and they know everything about him

574
00:33:27,282 --> 00:33:31,055
Interviewer: When you left, were your deposited belongings complete, or did they take anything?

575
00:33:31,590 --> 00:33:32,590
No, no

576
00:33:32,983 --> 00:33:36,869
I had only a ring, a watch, and a phone, and I took them

577
00:33:37,399 --> 00:33:38,399
Nothing was missing?

578
00:33:38,586 --> 00:33:41,765
No, no, my belongings were in an envelope and my name was written on it

579
00:33:41,869 --> 00:33:43,435
Interviewer: Did they take you home, or did they leave you here?

580
00:33:43,509 --> 00:33:46,672
No, no, they took me to the street and left me

581
00:33:47,689 --> 00:33:48,969
They didn’t use this method with you?

582
00:33:49,096 --> 00:33:51,392
No, no, they left me at 11 p.m.

583
00:33:51,465 --> 00:33:53,719
Interviewer: Did you know that you would be released that day? Witness: No

584
00:33:54,663 --> 00:33:56,110
Interviewer: Did you find out directly and suddenly?

585
00:33:56,184 --> 00:33:57,637
Suddenly, before you know it, he’s calling

586
00:33:57,848 --> 00:34:01,801
I told you, sometimes two come and call someone to take him; they might not bring him back, or they might bring him back

587
00:34:02,208 --> 00:34:03,208
Or they transfer him somewhere else

588
00:34:03,588 --> 00:34:08,335
Interviewer: From the moment they took you out of the room until they took you out of the prison

589
00:34:09,076 --> 00:34:12,886
Were your hands tied, or were you free when they took you out?

590
00:34:13,053 --> 00:34:16,559
When they release you, they only blindfold you until you reach the start of the street

591
00:34:16,642 --> 00:34:18,089
They remove the blindfold and tell you–Go

592
00:34:20,266 --> 00:34:25,144
Interviewer: Tell me about the moment when you met your mother and your wife

593
00:34:25,270 --> 00:34:28,337
And they met you after you had been missing for a long time, and they didn’t know what had happened to you

594
00:34:29,077 --> 00:34:31,643
How did you handle this situation, and how did they receive you?

595
00:34:31,811 --> 00:34:33,955
By God, it was an indescribable feeling

596
00:34:34,962 --> 00:34:36,047
Something indescribable

597
00:34:36,107 --> 00:34:37,921
Is your mother alive? Witness: Yes, thank God

598
00:34:37,973 --> 00:34:38,973
Interviewer: How did they receive you?

599
00:34:39,446 --> 00:34:42,559
The situation at home was like hell

600
00:34:43,932 --> 00:34:47,664
They didn’t know my fate—one person would tell them one thing, and another would tell them I was detained

601
00:34:47,758 --> 00:34:49,782
And another says they killed him, and another says they threw him into Khafsa

602
00:34:49,910 --> 00:34:52,380
And another says they will execute them

603
00:34:52,500 --> 00:34:56,555
So whenever someone is executed, they start thinking about me

604
00:34:56,655 --> 00:34:57,888
So my family’s minds are all scattered

605
00:35:02,758 --> 00:35:08,474
Interviewer: After you served your time in prison, how did your life change?

606
00:35:08,565 --> 00:35:10,251
Is your life the same as before prison?

607
00:35:10,343 --> 00:35:14,566
No, but I’ve started to feel that I’m being watched, and so on

608
00:35:17,452 --> 00:35:23,618
Interviewer: Didn’t you develop a nervous or hysterical condition

609
00:35:23,685 --> 00:35:25,605
After you were released, or any specific mental illness?

610
00:35:25,712 --> 00:35:30,686
No, but I feel my nerves are tense to this day

611
00:35:33,359 --> 00:35:36,699
Interviewer: Is the way you deal with your wife and kids the same as before prison?

612
00:35:36,899 --> 00:35:40,289
I mean your relationship with them, in terms of mindset and behavior?

613
00:35:40,321 --> 00:35:42,840
No, there is none of that

614
00:35:43,182 --> 00:35:45,009
Interviewer: Did they notice any kind of change in you?

615
00:35:45,531 --> 00:35:50,132
Only sometimes I get moments of nervous tension, as soon as I get annoyed by something

616
00:35:50,193 --> 00:35:53,594
Interviewer: Your closest person, your wife—did she tell you that you weren’t like this before?

617
00:35:53,720 --> 00:35:55,884
Yes, I wasn’t like this before, I don’t even have any patience

618
00:35:56,198 --> 00:36:02,039
Now wherever I am, I have no patience, I don’t like to talk much about any topic

619
00:36:02,915 --> 00:36:06,196
Interviewer: Did it happen to you after you were released, that in the morning when you wake up

620
00:36:06,503 --> 00:36:08,183
You wake in the morning and can’t open your eyes?

621
00:36:08,736 --> 00:36:11,275
Afraid that you’re still in prison and you were dreaming you got out?

622
00:36:11,721 --> 00:36:15,274
By God, talking about those things—when I was detained and when I was released

623
00:36:15,345 --> 00:36:17,337
A big problem, and the hardest feeling

624
00:36:17,711 --> 00:36:21,437
When I got home, they hadn’t expected that I would come back
